summary.name: Bacteria_Antibiotic_Sensitivity
summary.dataset_description: This dataset contains information about the sensitivity of various bacteria to different antibiotics.

properties.description: The name of the bacterial species.
The minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of penicillin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria (in micrograms per milliliter).
The minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of streptomycin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria (in micrograms per milliliter).
The minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of neomycin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria (in micrograms per milliliter).
The result of the Gram staining test, which classifies bacteria as either Gram-positive or Gram-negative based on the characteristics of their cell walls.
The genus of the bacterial species.

goals.question: What is the distribution of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of penicillin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria?
goals.rationale: This tells us about the range of MIC values for penicillin and how effective it is against the different bacterial species.

goals.question: What is the distribution of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of streptomycin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria?
goals.rationale: This tells us about the range of MIC values for streptomycin and how effective it is against the different bacterial species.

goals.question: What is the distribution of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of neomycin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria?
goals.rationale: This tells us about the range of MIC values for neomycin and how effective it is against the different bacterial species.

goals.question: What is the distribution of bacterial species based on their Gram staining test results?
goals.rationale: This tells us about the proportion of Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacterial species in the dataset.

goals.question: What is the distribution of bacterial species based on their genus?
goals.rationale: This tells us about the proportion of different bacterial genera in the dataset and their sensitivity to different antibiotics.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Penicillin', kde=True, bins=20)
    plt.axvline(data['Penicillin'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {data['Penicillin'].median():.2f}")
    plt.title("What is the distribution of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of penicillin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria?", wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Streptomycin', kde=True, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(data['Streptomycin'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {data['Streptomycin'].median():.2f}")
    plt.title("What is the distribution of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of streptomycin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria?", wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Neomycin', kde=True, bins=20)
    median_neomycin = data['Neomycin'].median()
    plt.axvline(median_neomycin, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Median: {median_neomycin:.2f}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of neomycin required to inhibit the growth of the bacteria?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    gram_counts = data['Gram_Staining'].value_counts()
    sns.barplot(x=gram_counts.index, y=gram_counts.values)
    plt.xlabel('Gram Staining')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of bacterial species based on their Gram staining test results?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    chart = sns.countplot(x='Genus', data=data, palette='viridis')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of bacterial species based on their genus?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Genus')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.legend(title='Genus', loc='upper right', labels=data['Genus'].unique())
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
